{
  "document_id": "prov-16",
  "title": "Proverbs 16",
  "type": "study-bible",
  "translation": "Oxford",
  "blocks": [
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-heading-17",
      "type": "heading",
      "text": "17"
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-2",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 2,
      "text": "All one's ways may be pure in one's own eyes, but the Lord weighs the spirit."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-4",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "2 : , see 1.15n. , see 3.7n. (Heb “ruaḥ”), lit., “breath,” a person's temperament (cf. 1.23; 15.13; 18.14). , i.e., examines (21.2; 24.12; cf. 17.3).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 2,
      "verse_end": 2
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-3",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 3,
      "text": "Commit your work to the Lord, and your plans will be established."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-4",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 4,
      "text": "The Lord has made everything for its purpose, even the wicked for the day of trouble."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-5",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "4 : , i.e., when God has need of it; see Sir 39.16–35.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 4,
      "verse_end": 4
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-5",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 5,
      "text": "All those who are arrogant are an abomination to the Lord; be assured, they will not go unpunished."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-6",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "5 : , see 3.7n. , see 3.32n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 5,
      "verse_end": 5
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-6",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 6,
      "text": "By loyalty and faithfulness iniquity is atoned for, and by the fear of the Lord one avoids evil."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-7",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "6 : , see 3.33; 14.22. , see 1.7n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 6,
      "verse_end": 6
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-7",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 7,
      "text": "When the ways of people please the Lord, he causes even their enemies to be at peace with them."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-8",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 8,
      "text": "Better is a little with righteousness than large income with injustice."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-8",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "8 : , see 12.9n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 8,
      "verse_end": 8
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-9",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 9,
      "text": "The human mind plans the way, but the Lord directs the steps."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-2",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "16.1–9: Proverbs about God's sovereignty.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 9
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-9",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "9 : See v. 1.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 9,
      "verse_end": 9
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-10",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 10,
      "text": "Inspired decisions are on the lips of a king; his mouth does not sin in judgment."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-11",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 11,
      "text": "Honest balances and scales are the Lord's; all the weights in the bag are his work."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-11",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "11 : , see 11.1n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 11,
      "verse_end": 11
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-12",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 12,
      "text": "It is an abomination to kings to do evil, for the throne is established by righteousness."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-13",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 13,
      "text": "Righteous lips are the delight of a king, and he loves those who speak what is right."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-12",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "12–13 : , i.e., they loathe it. Kings were responsible for establishing and maintaining justice (e.g., 20.8; 25.5; 29.4, 14).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 12,
      "verse_end": 13
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-14",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 14,
      "text": "A king's wrath is a messenger of death, and whoever is wise will appease it."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-13",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "14 : The king's wrath was ferocious and potentially devastating (cf. 14.35; 19.12; 20.2; 24.21–22).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 14,
      "verse_end": 14
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-15",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 15,
      "text": "In the light of a king's face there is life, and his favor is like the clouds that bring the spring rain."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-10",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "10–15 : Proverbs about the king.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 10,
      "verse_end": 15
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-14",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "15 : to nourish the first crops was considered a blessing from God (Deut 11.14; Joel 2.23; cf. Jer 3.3).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 15,
      "verse_end": 15
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-16",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 16,
      "text": "How much better to get wisdom than gold! To get understanding is to be chosen rather than silver."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-16",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "16 : , see 2.4n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 16,
      "verse_end": 16
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-17",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 17,
      "text": "The highway of the upright avoids evil; those who guard their way preserve their lives."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-18",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 18,
      "text": "Pride goes before destruction, and a haughty spirit before a fall."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-19",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 19,
      "text": "It is better to be of a lowly spirit among the poor than to divide the spoil with the proud."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-17",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "18–19 : See 11.2n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 18,
      "verse_end": 19
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-20",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 20,
      "text": "Those who are attentive to a matter will prosper, and happy are those who trust in the Lord."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-21",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 21,
      "text": "The wise of heart is called perceptive, and pleasant speech increases persuasiveness."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-18",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "21 : , lit., “sweet lips”; see v. 24. Contrast the strange woman's flattering speech (see 2.16n.; 5.3; 7.5,22).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 21,
      "verse_end": 21
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-22",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 22,
      "text": "Wisdom is a fountain of life to one who has it, but folly is the punishment of fools."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-19",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "22 : , see 10.11n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 22,
      "verse_end": 22
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-23",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 23,
      "text": "The mind of the wise makes their speech judicious, and adds persuasiveness to their lips."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-24",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 24,
      "text": "Pleasant words are like a honeycomb, sweetness to the soul and health to the body."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-15",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "16–24 : Various virtues.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 16,
      "verse_end": 24
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-20",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "24 : , see 2.10n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 24,
      "verse_end": 24
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-25",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 25,
      "text": "Sometimes there is a way that seems to be right, but in the end it is the way to death."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-21",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "25 : See 14.12.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 25,
      "verse_end": 25
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-26",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 26,
      "text": "The appetite of workers works for them; their hunger urges them on."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-22",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "26 : The relentless press of hunger, see Eccl 6.7.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 26,
      "verse_end": 26
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-27",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 27,
      "text": "Scoundrels concoct evil, and their speech is like a scorching fire."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-24",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "27 : , see 6.12–15. Scorching speech, see 26.18–19.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 27,
      "verse_end": 27
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-28",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 28,
      "text": "A perverse person spreads strife, and a whisperer separates close friends."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-25",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "28 : , i.e., a gossip; see 11.13; 17.9; 18.8; 20.19; 26.22; Sir 27.16–21.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 28,
      "verse_end": 28
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-29",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 29,
      "text": "The violent entice their neighbors, and lead them in a way that is not good."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-30",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 30,
      "text": "One who winks the eyes plans perverse things; one who compresses the lips brings evil to pass."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-23",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "27–30 : Three dangerous types of people (cf. 6.12–19).",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 27,
      "verse_end": 30
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-26",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "30 : Body language hints at character. , see 6.13n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 30,
      "verse_end": 30
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-31",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 31,
      "text": "Gray hair is a crown of glory; it is gained in a righteous life."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-27",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "31 : , see 12.4n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 31,
      "verse_end": 31
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-32",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 32,
      "text": "One who is slow to anger is better than the mighty, and one whose temper is controlled than one who captures a city."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-28",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "32 : See 14.29n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 32,
      "verse_end": 32
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-33",
      "type": "verse",
      "number": 33,
      "text": "The lot is cast into the lap, but the decision is the Lord's alone."
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-1",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "10.1–22.16: The proverbs of Solomon. Comprised predominantly of two-line proverbs, the oldest section of Proverbs can be divided into 10.1–15.33, which features antithetical proverbs, and 16.1–22.16, which includes a mix of proverbial forms.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 1,
      "verse_end": 33
    },
    {
      "block_id": "oxford-prov-16-h1kj-29",
      "type": "commentary",
      "text": "33 : , see 1.14n.",
      "canonical_ref": {
        "work": "bible",
        "book": "prov",
        "chapter": 16
      },
      "verse_start": 33,
      "verse_end": 33
    }
  ]
}